{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chart-page-js","path":"/hyperbolic-tree","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>is a method of visualizing a hierarchy as a tree positioned on a hyperbolic plane and mapping this plane onto a circular display region. The hyperbolic tree has its root initially in the center, but the display can be transformed to bring other nodes into focus. Hyperbolic trees are often used to display webinformation.\nThe advantage of hyperbolic tree interactive graphics is the possibility to display a large amount of hierarchical information within a small space without a loss of focus and context.</p>\n<!--more-->\n<h2 id=\"origin\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#origin\" aria-label=\"origin permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Origin</h2>\n<p>The inspiration for the hyperbolic tree came from a woodcut print by Dutch graphic artist Maurits Cornelis Escher (1898-1972) known mathematically-inspired woodcuts. The woodcut is known as <a href=\"https://www.mcescher.com/gallery/recognition-success/circle-limit-iv/\">Circle Limit IV</a> created in 1960.</p>\n<h2 id=\"further-reading\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#further-reading\" aria-label=\"further reading permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V